<div id="review_1428561296" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1428561296" />
    <a title="Esil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3643764-esil"><img alt="Esil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1443746908p2/3643764.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1428561296?book_show_action=true">Oct 29, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Esil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Esil" href="/user/show/3643764-esil">Esil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3643764-esil?shelf=netgalley">netgalley</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1428561296" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6081153805968795679">3 1/2 stars. I&apos;ve read a few other GR reviews describe Summit Lake as a good debut, and I completely agree. It&apos;s a fast paced engaging read that has a few flaws that can be excused given that this is a debut. The novel begins with the murder and rape of first year law student Becca -- for those who might be turned off by this description of the opening, note that the violence is not too graphic and this is really the only real violence in the book. The rest of the book alternates between two tim</span>
  <span id="freeText6081153805968795679" style="display:none">3 1/2 stars. I've read a few other GR reviews describe Summit Lake as a good debut, and I completely agree. It's a fast paced engaging read that has a few flaws that can be excused given that this is a debut. The novel begins with the murder and rape of first year law student Becca -- for those who might be turned off by this description of the opening, note that the violence is not too graphic and this is really the only real violence in the book. The rest of the book alternates between two time lines involving the events leading up to the murder and the investigation following the murder by true crime journalist Kelsey. Becca's story focuses on the dynamics between a small group of university friends in the year preceding the murder, and Kelsey's investigation works to overcome clear attempts by the police to cover up what really happened. I found it very readable and not overly formulaic, and there were some good unexpected turns. As for the flaws that reveal this one as a debut: there is a very improbable unnecessary coincidence toward the end, and there were a few loose ends that could have been tidied up, but this was certainly a good debut. I would definitely consider reading Charlie Donlea's next book. Thank you to the publisher and Netgalley for an opportunity to read an advance copy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6081153805968795679" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


