  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3708056688" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3708056688" />
    <a title="Kat (Books are Comfort Food)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25532045-kat-books-are-comfort-food"><img alt="Kat (Books are Comfort Food)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1617935580p2/25532045.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3708056688?book_show_action=true">Jan 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kat (Books are Comfort Food)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kat (Books are Comfort Food)" href="/user/show/25532045-kat-books-are-comfort-food">Kat (Books are Comfort Food)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/34697709-summit-lake">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3708056688" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14672016856360539763">Loved it! <br/><br/>Becca Eckersley, a law student at George Washington University, travels to a cabin on a lake to cram for final exams. She is left savagely beaten and strangled after she makes a confession to someone at the local coffee house. Was the confession the start of a landslide that couldn’t be stopped? <br/><br/>The police weren’t doing much to solve the murder and seemed to be more interested in hiding important details. I guess no one wants too much limelight, especially if you are a clout-toting, le</span>
  <span id="freeText14672016856360539763" style="display:none">Loved it! <br /><br />Becca Eckersley, a law student at George Washington University, travels to a cabin on a lake to cram for final exams. She is left savagely beaten and strangled after she makes a confession to someone at the local coffee house. Was the confession the start of a landslide that couldn’t be stopped? <br /><br />The police weren’t doing much to solve the murder and seemed to be more interested in hiding important details. I guess no one wants too much limelight, especially if you are a clout-toting, legal mogul father, who has his sights set on a judgeship.<br /><br />Enter, Kelsey Castle, a crime reporter and author, who was sent to look into the story and circumstances surrounding Becca’s death. No, this wasn’t the fluff piece she anticipated, and Kelsey genuinely wanted justice, for the perpetrator to pay for stomping out a life that was barely coming into its own. <br /><br />The characters were enjoyable and even though I was concerned that this would be college kids, partying to the point something blowing up, I was happy to be wrong. For every action there is a reaction, of course, and some of the reactions weren’t thoroughly thought through and that meant trouble.<br /><br />I also wondered about secrets and trust. Some secrets are best hidden. But aren’t some secrets, that in our paranoia, we hold too tightly to our hearts? Sometimes, we have to trust those that love us. The “what t if’s” plagued me in this story.<br /><br />Transfixed, I was, by the mood of Summit Lake and the beautiful town surrounding it that had an atmosphere all its own. A small, close-knit community with caring and interesting characters. Of course they knew what’s going on with everyone, but who can refuse the comfort of friends, sweet tea and fresh baked scones?<br /><br />The surroundings of the lake brought back many childhood memories for me as there is nothing like summer vacations mixed with water! Sun, skipping over the water, the spot where a waterfall takes center stage when the sun is angled just right and feelings that lure us to slip off shoes and enjoy the soft, warm embrace of water. <br /><br />Book pacing is always an issue (for me), but here each page I turned lured me farther into the deep end. <br /><br />Yeah, I felt like a smarty-pants, trying to figure out the ending in advance. I was left with a humility cookie, which was A-OK, because I love cookies and I was rewarded with more secrets. Good authors make you work for it. <br /><br />In closing this was a wonderful debut from Charlie Donlea. I loved the book, each chapter left me wanting more. I was sad when I reached the end, sorry to leave the lake and a beautiful young woman who did not have the opportunity to reach her full potential. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14672016856360539763" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


